{{short description|Ancient Greek mythological figure}}
[[File:Aganippe LACMA M.88.91.381p.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Aganippe%20LACMA%20M.88.91.381p.jpg|thumb|''Aganippe'' by Philip Galle (Holland, Haarlem, 1537-1612)|283x283px]]
'''Aganippe''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|g|ʌ|n|ɪ|p|iː}}; {{lang-grc|Ἀγανίππη}}) was the name of both a spring and the [[Naiad]] (a [[Crinaeae|Crinaea]]) associated with it. The spring is in [[Boeotia]], near [[Thespiae]], at the base of [[Mount Helicon]],<ref>[[Pliny the Elder]], ''[[Natural History (encyclopedia)|Natural History]]'', [http://topostext.org/work.php?work_id=148 4.12.1].</ref> and was associated with the [[Muses]] who were sometimes called Aganippides. Drinking from it was considered to be  a source of poetic inspiration.  The nymph is called a daughter of the river-god [[Permessus]] (called [[Termessus]] by Pausanias).<ref>Smith, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0104%3Aalphabetic+letter%3DA%3Aentry+group%3D9%3Aentry%3Daganippe-bio-1 "Aganippe" 1.]; [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]]. ''Description of Greece'', [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text;jsessionid=05B843EF34498A9A89570868F9E514B9?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160%3Abook%3D9%3Achapter%3D29%3Asection%3D5 9.29.5]; [[Virgil]]. ''[[Bucolics|Eclogues]]'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Verg.+Ecl.+10&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0057 10.12]</ref> [[Ovid]] associates Aganippe with [[Hippocrene]].<ref>[[Ovid]], ''[[Fasti (poem)|Fasti]]'' [http://www.theoi.com/Text/OvidFasti5.html 5.7].</ref>

