{{Location map | Indian Ocean | lat_dir = S | lat_deg = 31 | lon_dir = E | lon_deg = 95}} [[File:Seir.png|thumb|Map of the Southeast Indian Ridge. Broken Ridge is the green area in the upper left corner.]] '''Broken Ridge''' or '''Broken Plateau''' is an [[oceanic plateau]] in the south-eastern [[Indian Ocean]]. Broken Ridge once formed a [[large igneous province]] (LIP) together with the [[Kerguelen Plateau]]. When Australia and Antarctica started to separate, Broken Ridge and the Kerguelen Plateau got separated by the [[Southeast Indian Ridge]].<ref name="Schlich">{{Harvnb|Schlich|2013|p=79-80}}</ref> [[Alkalic]] [[basalt]] from Broken Ridge has been dated to 95 Ma.<ref name="Frey-etal-p15-17" />
Broken Ridge stretches {{Convert|1200|km|abbr=on}} from the southern end of [[Ninety East Ridge]] towards the south-western corner of [[Australia]]. It is up to {{Convert|400|km|abbr=on}} wide and reaches {{Convert|1000|m|abbr=on}} below sea level. It is separated from the [[Diamantina Fracture Zone]] on its southern side by a {{Convert|3000|m|abbr=on}} escarpment, while on the northern side the ridge slopes gently towards the abyssal [[Wharton Basin]]. The sediment cover on the ridge reaches {{Convert|800|m|abbr=on}} and the [[Mohorovičić discontinuity|Moho]] is found at about {{Convert|20|km|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Schlich" /> It is separated from the [[Naturaliste Plateau]] by the [[Dirck Hartog Ridge]].
The Kerguelen LIP covered {{Convert|2.3|e6km2|abbr=on}} making it the second largest LIP on Earth (after the [[Ontong Java Plateau]] in the Pacific).<ref name="Ingle-2007">{{Harvnb|Ingle|2007}}</ref> Both these enormous LIPs reaches {{Convert|2|–|4|km|abbr=on}} above the surrounding ocean floor and have a crustal thickness of {{Convert|20|-|40|km|abbr=on}} (compared to oceanic crust typically around {{Convert|7|km|abbr=on}} thick.)<ref name="Frey-etal-2000-intro">{{Harvnb|Frey|Coffin|Wallace|Weis|2000|loc=Introduction, pp. 74–77}}</ref> The Broken Ridge and Kerguelen Plateau are now separated by {{Convert|1800|km|abbr=on}}. When they broke-up, the southern flank of Broken Ridge was uplifted some {{Convert|2000|m|abbr=on}} and reached above sea level.<ref name="Frey-etal-2000-intro" />
The Kerguelen LIP has a long and complicated history, however, and is probably the least "typical" of all LIPs.<ref name="Ingle-2007">{{Harvnb|Ingle|2007}}</ref> Rocks from both the Broken Ridge and the Kerguelen Plateau contain a continental component or "fingerprint". In the Early Cretaceous, the [[Kerguelen hotspot]] was split into several [[diapir]]s of various sizes, composition, and ascent rates. These separate diapirs created the [[Bunbury Basalt]], the Southern Kerguelen Plateau, the [[Rajmahal Traps]]/Indian [[lamprophyre]]s, Antarctic lamprophyres, and the Central Kerguelen Plateau/Broken Ridge. In the late Cretaceous, activity in the mantle slowed and the Kerguelen hotspot was reduced to a single plume which created the Ninety East Ridge.<ref name="Frey-etal-p15-17">{{Harvnb|Frey|Coffin|Wallace|Weis|2003|loc=Mantle sources, plume-lithosphere interactions, and plume models, pp. 15-17}}</ref> 120-95 Ma when the Southern and Central Kerguelen Plateau formed together with the Broken Ridge, the Kerguelen hotspot produced {{Convert|1|km3|abbr=on}}/year, but 95-25 Ma the output decreased to {{Convert|0.1|km3|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Harvnb|Frey|Coffin|Wallace|Weis|2003|p=18}}</ref>
